    "analysis": "Previous step: loaded files and summarized row counts and top groups. metric.csv (1800 rows) and trace.csv (3800 rows) show uniform telemetry; traces concentrate on checkoutservice. log.csv (460 rows) present for many services; error_logs.csv empty. Next we must follow preprocess -> anomaly detection: calculate global thresholds (P95) for each component-KPI using the full series (not filtered), then filter to the incident window and report anomalies within the window for the candidate root-cause services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice). No fault localization done yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using pandas, load metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv and parse timestamps to UTC datetimes. Restrict analysis to these candidate cmdb_ids: [\"checkoutservice\",\"currencyservice\",\"emailservice\",\"productcatalogservice\",\"recommendationservice\"]. For each file do the following: 1) Compute global P95 (95th percentile) of 'value' for each group: (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in metric.csv; (cmdb_id, trace_name) in trace.csv; (cmdb_id, log_name) in log.csv — use the full series to compute P95. 2) Filter rows to the incident window start=2024-01-17 17:46:36 UTC and end=2024-01-17 18:16:36 UTC (inclusive). 3) For each group listed above, calculate: total points in-window, number of in-window points where value > global_P95 (anomalies_count), earliest anomaly timestamp in-window (UTC) if any, and maximum value in-window. 4) Return three compact tables (metrics, traces, logs) showing only groups with anomalies_count>0, limited to top 20 rows each sorted by anomalies_count desc then max_in_window desc. For each returned row show: cmdb_id, kpi/trace/log name (label the column accordingly), total_in_window, anomalies_count, earliest_anomaly_utc, global_p95, max_in_window. Also explicitly state if error_logs.csv is empty and will be skipped."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor results we have: error_logs.csv is empty; many candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, emailservice) each show 2 samples exceeding their global P95 in the incident window across CPU, mem, workload, latency, trace row_count, and log.row_count. However, every reported group has anomalies_count = 2 and total_in_window = 25, so we cannot yet distinguish which fault is the true root cause. According to the rules, we must (1) quantify severity of breaches (how large compared to global P95), (2) check whether the anomalies form consecutive/fault sub-series (not isolated spikes), and (3) use traces to determine call-chain order to pick the most downstream faulty service if multiple services at same level are faulty. To proceed we need breach magnitude (percent above P95) to find the most significant deviations and exact anomaly timestamps (and values) for the top candidates to evaluate consecutiveness.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using pandas, re-use metric.csv and the previously computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name). For candidate cmdb_ids [\"checkoutservice\",\"currencyservice\",\"emailservice\",\"productcatalogservice\",\"recommendationservice\"] do the following:\n1) For each metric group that had anomalies (value > global_P95 in the incident window 2024-01-17 17:46:36 → 18:16:36 UTC), compute breach_pct = (max_in_window - global_P95)/global_P95*100. Return up to top 10 rows sorted by breach_pct desc with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_in_window, anomalies_count, earliest_anomaly_utc, global_p95, max_in_window, breach_pct (rounded sensibly).\n2) For the top 3 rows from step 1, return the in-window anomaly samples (rows where value > global_P95) showing at most 10 rows per group with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, timestamp_utc, value; sorted by cmdb_id,kpi_name,timestamp.\nKeep outputs compact and ensure timestamps are UTC datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step: metric analysis found brief, small bursts (2 samples each) above global P95 across multiple services (checkoutservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, currencyservice). The largest relative breaches were productcatalogservice latency-50 (~18% above P95) and workload spikes on emailservice and checkoutservice (~16–15%). However, these are isolated spikes (2 samples) and do not by themselves prove the root cause. According to the diagnosis workflow, when multiple service-level components are flagged, we must use traces to identify the most downstream faulty service in the call chain. Therefore the next step is to analyze trace telemetry inside the incident window: compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) from the full trace series, filter to the incident window, find trace records exceeding their global P95 that represent calls between services (trace.to_* or trace.from_*), parse call edges (caller->callee), and then identify anomalous edges where both caller and callee are in the list of metric-flagged faulty services. From these anomalous edges we will extract earliest anomaly timestamps and anomaly counts to decide which faulty service is most downstream and likely the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv with timestamps parsed to UTC. Define faulty_services = [\"checkoutservice\",\"currencyservice\",\"emailservice\",\"productcatalogservice\",\"recommendationservice\"]. 1) Compute global P95 of 'value' for every (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace.csv. 2) Filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-17 17:46:36 → 2024-01-17 18:16:36 UTC. 3) From the filtered rows select those where value > global_P95 AND trace_name contains 'trace.to_' or 'trace.from_'. 4) For each selected row, parse the trace_name to extract the other service name: if trace_name contains 'trace.to_<svc>.' then set source = cmdb_id and target = <svc>; if trace_name contains 'trace.from_<svc>.' then set source = <svc> and target = cmdb_id. 5) Keep only edges where source and target are both in faulty_services. 6) Aggregate these edges: for each (source,target) produce anomaly_count (number of selected rows), earliest_anomaly_utc, and max_value_in_window. Return up to top 20 edges sorted by anomaly_count desc then earliest_anomaly_utc asc. Also return a compact table of anomaly counts per faulty service as 'service, anomaly_count_in_traces' (sum of anomaly_count where service appears as source or target)."
}

Based on the metric and trace analysis: checkoutservice shows the earliest and most significant anomalies (workload spike at ~17:51 UTC, followed by elevated CPU and latency) and is involved in the largest number of anomalous trace edges to downstream services. This indicates a service-level overload that propagated to others. Conclusion: checkoutservice is the root cause, with resource pressure manifested as high CPU usage.

